ant of Old French <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Towards the end of the Middle Ages this form became largely confined to Scotland. In the 20th century it became more widely used in the English-speaking world and enjoyed a period of great popularity, but it is now out of fashion. Among numerous well-known and influential bearers are the British novelists  Jean Plaidy  (  Eleanor Hibbert ,  1910–93 ) and  Jean Rhys  (  Ella Gwendolen Rees Williams ,  1894–1979 ), British actress  Jean Simmons  (  1929–2010 ), and American-born actress  Jean Seberg  (  1938–79 ). It is also found as a variant spelling of the masculine name   Gene ."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]},{"name":"Jeane","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jean ."]}]},{"name":"1er","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from Yiddish <i>ber</i> ‘bear’, probably influenced by the early medieval European practice of giving animal names to people. It is often paired with   Dov   in order to provide a Hebrew name in certain rituals."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Jean 1er DE QUIERET-DE NOUVION was born in 1161, his father, Adam II DE QUIERET-GEORGERY, was 33 and his mother, Havoise DE NOUVION EN PONTHIEU-DE MONTCAVREL, was 26. He married Elisabeth de Gamaches in 1188. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1224, at the age of 63."},"et":{"1161–1224":"1161–1224","1171–1231":"1171–1231","1194–1251":"1194–1251","1128–1190":"1128–1190","1135–1188":"1135–1188","1190":"1190","1128":"1128","1224":"1224","1135":"1135","1188":"1188","1231":"1231","1251":"1251","1161":"1161","1194":"1194","1171":"1171"},"fi":{"1161–1224":"1161–1224","1171–1231":"1171–1231","1194–1251":"1194–1251","1128–1190":"1128–1190","1135–1188":"1135–1188","1190":"1190","1128":"1128","1224":"1224","1135":"1135","11